'''Speedway Park''', also known as '''Jacksonville Speedway''', was a {{convert|0.5|mi|adj=on}} dirt oval auto racing track, located in [[Jacksonville, Florida]].<ref>"[https://books.google.com/books?id=JyAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA81&dq=%22Speedway+Park%22+Jacksonville&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9p9hU9nmH4ijsQSH-ICYCA&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Speedway%20Park%22%20Jacksonville&f=false Auto Race Tracks]". ''[[Billboard (magazine)|The Billboard]]'', April 13, 1957, page 81.</ref>

Opened in 1947, the track was located at the intersection of Lenox Avenue and Plymouth Street in southwest Jacksonville.<ref>Coble, Don. "[http://brainerddispatch.com/sports/auto-racing/2011-06-27/yarbrough-lived-and-raced-fast-fell-even-faster Yarbrough lived and raced fast, fell even faster]". June 27, 2011. Brainerd, MN: ''[[Brainerd Dispatch]]''. Accessed 2014-05-01.</ref> [[NASCAR]] [[Grand National Series]] (now Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series) races were held at the track during the 1951, 1952, 1954, 1955, 1961 and 1964 seasons.<ref name="RR">"[http://www.racing-reference.info/tracks/Speedway_Park Race Results at Speedway Park]". ''Racing-Reference''. USA Today Sports Media Group. Accessed 2014-05-01.</ref> The final Grand National Series race at the track was won by [[Wendell Scott]], the only African-American to win in NASCAR's top series.<ref name="Jax1">{{cite web|url=http://members.jacksonville.com/news/metro/2010-06-27/story/1963-nascar-controversy-racing-or-race |title=1963 NASCAR controversy: Racing or race?|work=[[The Florida Times-Union]]|location=Jacksonville, FL|date=June 27, 2010|accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref>

In addition to auto racing, the track hosted the Duval County Exposition.<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=4AoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA47&dq=%22Speedway+Park%22+Jacksonville&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9p9hU9nmH4ijsQSH-ICYCA&ved=0CEMQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22Speedway%20Park%22%20Jacksonville&f=false The Billboard]'', October 20, 1958, page 47.</ref> The [[NASCAR Grand American]] Series also competed there.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1873&dat=19701004&id=1E4fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ndEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3942,812710|title=Lund Wins|date=October 4, 1970|work=[[Daytona Beach Sunday News-Journal]]|page=2D|accessdate=2014-05-01|location=Daytona Beach, FL}}</ref> After a final NASCAR [[Grand National East Series]] race in 1972 won by [[David Pearson (racing driver)|David Pearson]],<ref name="RR"/> the track was closed in 1973; a housing development now stands at the site.<ref>Allaway, Phil. "[http://frontstretch.com/site/29041/the-critics-annex-39-wendell-scott-a-race-story The Critic's Annex: 39-Wendell Scott: A Race Story]". February 23, 2011. ''Frontstretch''. Accessed 2014-05-01.</ref>

